Concerns regarding treatment at A&E on 14th July 2025, when arrived by ambulance with a numb left foot, no sensation, and inability to move toes.
1.	Fall under paramedic care: While being assisted out of the ambulance, ankle collapsed and fell, causing immediate pain.
2.	X ray confirmation: The radiographer informed  that the X ray clearly showed a fracture in my ankle and explained possible treatments (cast, boot, CT scan, surgery).
3.	Dismissal by doctor: Despite visible swelling and X ray evidence, the doctor refused treatment, claiming  injury was "psychological," denied mobility aids, and refused a second opinion.
4.	Unsafe discharge:  left to leave A&E unsupported, in visible distress, until a paramedic re intervened and directed me to another hospital.
5.	Outcome at second hospital: A second X ray at Russell Hays confirmed the fracture; I am now in a boot and referred to fracture clinic.
This represents a serious failure of duty of care, likely causing further pain and trauma. I request:
•	A full investigation into the A&E doctor's conduct;
•	Documentation and review of all clinical and radiological records;
•	Explanation of how the clear X ray findings were ignored;
•	Measures to prevent similar "psychological dismissal" of real injuries;
•	Confirmation that this is recorded as a Patient Safety Incident.

Complainant emailed re the failings in her 10 year old Son's treatment in A&E and Fracture Clinic which has resulted in potentially long-term issues; in particular the Complainant has detailed the below:
Poor decision-making and clinical judgment exercised during Euan's initial and follow-up care at Good Hope Hospital;
Why consistent concerns were not recorded in any correspondence;
why appropriate steps were not taken sooner to escalate or reassess his injury.

Patient's Daughter emailed on behalf of the deceased Patient's Family re the failings in her Mother's care and treatment at BHH prior to her death; Complainant lists the following issues:
Refusal to transfer to QEHB with specialist centre;
Poor diabetes management;
Inadequate management of symptoms;
Dehydration and cardiac effects;
Nutritional neglect;
Inadequate infection control;
Development of pressure sores;
Catheter mismanagement;
Failure to identify and manage sepsis;
End of life care and communication failures;
Complainant provided evidence re consent.

Patient's Mother emailed re poor care and treatment her Son has received under Urology in BHH, GHH and SH since June 2024, in particular she has raised the below:
Delays with appointments;
Inadequate Diagnostic Support (Patient is disabled);
Failure to Escalate and Respond to Deterioration;
Emergency and surgery complications due to delays;
Disorganised Aftercare and Communication Failures;
Impact on Rehabilitation of long-term critical illness and Mental Health.

Patient's Mother emailed re the poor standard of care and communication experienced whilst the Patient (her baby) was in the Neonatal Unit at BHH, in particular:
Lack of Support When Expressing;
Lack of Communication & Consent;
Unnotified Relocation;
Inadequate Cot;
Safety Incident: Monitor Falling;
Transfer Framed as a Cost-Saving Measure.

Patient emailed re poor care and treatment on Ward 726, QEHB; in particular:
Personal care failures;
Issues with medication and treatment;
Poor attitude of some Staff (Patient felt bullied and ignored);
Communication errors;
Patient witnessed safeguarding issues.

PATIENT'S DEATH IN HOSPITAL.
Deceased Patient's Niece and NOK emailed re her Aunt's poor care and treatment by a member of the nursing team on the Ward prior to her death and the lack of response from the Ward leadership team, in particular the Complainant raised the following:
•	Failure to prioritise people and respond to their individual needs;
•	Failure to practise effectively and administer prescribed medication appropriately;
•	Failure to treat patients and families with dignity, respect, and compassion;
•	Failure to communicate and support both patient and family during end-of-life care.

